review_blob: Big and juicy mango papaya with bitter grapefruit peel, nice drying bitterness to finish and balance out. Creamy mouthfeel. Near perfect.

Bottle from a cafe in Florence. Pours murky reddish yellow with a big bubbly head. Aroma and taste are a bit of bandaids, but not overwhelming. Flavor is funk, bandaids, a bit of fruit, dry funk. Light body. Overall this was a bit disappointing with the bandaid flavors.

Bottle at a cafe in Florence. Overall, a sweet red mess of a beer that I assume was because it had been sitting a while. Not bad at all, plenty drinkable, but just not very memorable. Better than the average beer.

Bottle at a cafe for lunch while in Rome. Overall a pretty decent amber lager, with sweet malts and smooth lager yeast notes. Nothing particularly special here, but I wouldnt turn one down if offered.

Pour from a bottle at the Baladin location in Rome. Brown pour, no head, into a Teku. Aroma of sweet caramel with lots of peaty smoke notes. Flavor is sweet caramel and smoke, lots of peat here, with beautiful oak and whiskey character. Rich body, low carbonation, really nice after dinner drink. Good stuff, but pricey for a bottle.

Bottle snagged on my trip to Seattle. Pours somewhat clear caramel color with a small off white head. Aroma is sweet honey, bourbon, harsh booze. Flavor is harsh booze, some slightly cloying malts, more harsh rubbing alcohol level booze. Mouthfeel is thinner than I would expect from this, and tough to choke down. Ultimately a drain pour after about 6 ounces of this. Yikes, this is rough.

2012 Bottle shared while at Brouwers in August 2015. Brown caramel color pour without any head on top. Aroma of bourbon and overly sweet malts. Flavor follows with some muddled sweet malts, a bit hot, a bit thin, and lots of oaky bourbon. Feel is on the thinner/harsh side overall, with little to no carbonation. I dont know if this was past its prime or what, but I was pretty disappointed. Not bad, but not up to expectations.

Bottle shared while at Brouwers. Pours deep dark brown color with a small off white head. Aroma is massive cinnamon and some light coffee, bourbon, sweet caramel. Flavor follows closely with huge cinnamon caramel flavors bursting through oaky bourbon and some earthy coffee in the backdrop. Rich and thick bodied, medium carbonation. This was excellent.
beer_name: Fremont Abominable - Bourbon Barrel Coffee Cinnamon

review_blob: Sampled at Brouwers. Hazy yellow pour, brett funk on the nose. Flavor is sweet with some brett funk, very different from anything Ive had. Its unique but not my favorite saison. Worth a try overall.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Bottle from Brouwers. A bit pricey at $35 but hey, I dont get to the left coast much. Pours clear copper colored without much head. Aroma is sweet honey and bourbon, not a lot else. Flavor follows with honeycomb and bourbon, a bit on the sweet side. Syrupy mouthfeel, very light carbonation. Overall a nice beer and glad to try it, but should have gotten this when I didnt already drink 32 ounces of barrel aged stouts and strong ales before it. Whoops.
beer_name: Hair of the Dog Bourbon Fred from the Wood

review_blob: On tap at Brouwers next to 15. Pours dark brown and almost black without much head. Aroma of some big roast, char, a bit of smoke, sweet chocolate and rich caramel notes, lots of oaky bourbon. Flavor follows the nose rather closely, with big rich sweet and roasty char flavors. Big mouthfeel, rich as hell, just beautiful. More please.

On tap at Brouwers alongside 18. Pours rich dark brown color without any head. Aroma is huge caramel and bourbon, rich malts, sweet brown sugar. Wow. Flavor follows closely with lots of vanilla marshmallow behind sweet rich caramel malts, a light hint of chocolate, and big bourbon sweetness, with a hint of oak in the backdrop. Big bodied, sweet and rich, low carbonation. Absolutely beautiful.

Sipped on a bottle of this on my first visit to Brouwers in Fremont. Pours pitch black with a creamy brown head. Huge earthy coffee aroma with lots of roast and chocolate and big bourbon notes, then more coffee. Flavor is a massive punch of coffee, super earthy, but big sweet tones of chocolate and lots of oaky bourbon coming through. Silky and rich mouthfeel, medium carbonation. One of the best beers I have ever had. Alongside Bourbon County Coffee for me, and perhaps eclipsing it. Beautiful!
beer_name: Fremont Dark Star - Bourbon Barrel Coffee Edition

review_blob: Grabbed a bottle from the brewery while in St. Pete running around. Pours deep dark pitch black with a dark brown head on top that sticks around a while. Aroma is huge chocolate and lots of roast there, not much bourbon to note but still some booze notes here, and some dry oakiness, with some sweetness to boot. Flavor follows with a huge rich chocolate burst, nice and rich body, a bit of ashy notes sort of like Zhukov, lots of sweetness, smooth oatmeal malt backdrop, lots of bitter roast to balance. I didnt get much bourbon here but I didnt care. This was a real winner for me.
beer_name: Green Bench Wood Parade Series: Manaphin

review_blob: 2014 version. Easily the best Eclipse variant Ive had. Much more body than most in the series. Pours black with light brown head, rich chocolate and dark fruit aroma with definite bourbon and oak. Flavor follows the nose, with a nice rich sweetness that I dont get from other versions of this beer. Not sure what happened in these barrels, but it managed to improve the beer substantially. This was nice.
beer_name: FiftyFifty Imperial Eclipse Stout - High West Bourbon Barrel

review_blob: On tap at the brewery. Pours pitch black without much head. Aroma is straight up buttered caramel popcorn. No sign of coconut or chocolate. Flavor is more chocolatey, with some caramel, spicy coffee notes and, yep, lots of butter. The buttery notes just ruin everything else. I get no coconut here, so not sure why it would be called Mounds. This could have had some really nice things going on with it, but then you have the Swamp Head QC that means one in every 4 beers or so is either sour or rancid in some way. So it goes. Ultimately, this didnt taste completely terrible, but I couldnt finish a glass.

Bottle from Catador membership. Pours pitch black with a two finger, creamy and fluffy light brown head. Aroma is huge barrel char, lots of bourbon, chocolate, coconut, rye, dark fruits. Flavor is lots of chocolate and some dark fruits, an interestingly light rye spicey note, huge char from the barrels, nicely integrate bourbon notes. Rich, though not as insanely thick as some CCB stouts, with low carbonation. Really, really nice. This is what the Eclipse series of beers SHOULD be if they had some body. Very similar fruity and big char notes on the flavor, but this blows away the Eclipse variants.
beer_name: Cigar City Endless Nameless Bourbon Barrel-Aged Imperial Stout

review_blob: I couldnt choke down more than a half ounce of this. Overly bitter, some weird fruit rind, rancid finish, no malt backing. there arent really any redeeming qualities here. No sweetness, no hop notes, just tastes like licking a dusty toilet with some bleach added. I love, love Crank, but almost every other IPA Ive had from these guys is just really sub-par. This takes the cake, though. Truly awful.

On tap at the brewery. This was not my cup of tea, with lots of fruit and low on the bitter, without much useful malt backing. It wasnt terrible, but nothing I would order again. Glad I had a smallish pour.

I was truly impressed at the flavors coming through despite the ABV here. Nice super light IPA if youre into session brews. As good or better than many others Ive had that are in the 4% range. Definitely worth a try if youre around. Green Bench is a neat place to stop, too.
beer_name: Green Bench De Soto Low Micro IPA

review_blob: On draft at the brewery. Not sure if there was something wrong with the keg I got poured, but definitely not what I expected from CCB. Extreme cloying sweetness that just sticks around on the palate, lots of fruit here, but no real roast or hop notes to balance the sweetness. I guess Im lost on why the reviews are so high on this one.
beer_name: Cigar City / Nantahala Two Regular Joes

review_blob: One of the more unique brews Ive had in a while. Pours deep orange color with no head. Aroma is lots of sweetness, the sauternes barrels come through heavily with big bold sweetness and thicken this thing up big time. The apricots are there both in the nose and the flavor, and go right alongisde the heavy sweetness from the barrels. Its still sour, with a bit of vinegar, and its actually kind of nice. Like drinking a dessert wine, but with a twist of sour apricots. Worth having, mainly in smaller samples, as one would with dessert wines anyway.
beer_name: Cigar City Swerve Sour Apricot Ale Aged in Sauternes Barrels

review_blob: On tap at the brewery. Pours pitch black with a nice dark brown head. Aroma of sweet lactose and lots of chocolate, roast, and even some hints of bitter coffee. Flavor follows that aroma very closely, its super rich, and has a clean roasty bitterness to finish things off and make you want to come back for more. One of the better brews theyve made recently.
beer_name: Cigar City Cow Boss Imperial Milk Stout

review_blob: Really nice in style beer here by CCB. Plenty of chocolate and fruit notes, with a more rich body than you might expect from the style. I really enjoyed this one with its light body and big flavors. Well done, guys.
beer_name: Cigar City The Bricks Five Year Beer

review_blob:
Fanta. Fanta. Wanna Fanta.

Seriously, I think this is just Fanta. 

This didnt taste bad. But the citrus punch flavors just dominated everything. There wasnt much white oak to speak of. Maybe there was a bit of hop note, but I couldnt tell if that was just the bitterness from the citrus or what. Fun novelty, but nothing more than that really.
beer_name: Cigar City White Oak Citrus Punch IPA

review_blob: The bourbon and smoke did not meld well together here, and I love smoked stouts as well as bourbon barrel stouts. Something is waaaay dry on the smoke side, and the barrels werent really picked up as much as the booze flavors themselves. Not terrible, but kinda meh.
beer_name: Xbeeriment Black Force One Bourbon Barrel Edition

review_blob: A bit on the brighter side than the previous version, and a pretty nice well rounded beer. Still plenty of punch and bitter, but pretty crushable for an imperial IPA. Not bad, Stone.

2014 bottle from shelves on my Vermont trip. Pours black with nice brown head. Aroma of lots of char, some fruity notes. Flavor follows with big char and sweetness. But this is way thin, even for an Eclipse variant. Its too bad they cant make a base beer that stands up to the barrels, because all the flavors here are really nice. Thicken this beer up, please.
beer_name: FiftyFifty Imperial Eclipse Stout - High West Rye Barrel

review_blob: This is perfect for those of you that like your beer to tastes like vomit. Peanut butter just isnt coming through here, and its more dry stale peanuts than sweet rich creamy peanut butter. Just not my bag.
beer_name: Belching Beaver Peanut Butter Milk Stout

review_blob: Hazy yellow pour, musty and sweet smells. Flavor is a bit on the sweet side, with some muddled brett. Overall decent saison, but just incredibly overshadowed by the other stuff out there these days.
Smells like butter. Tastes like butter. This is rancid. Really sad that they let this hit the market at all, knowing it was such a mess.

This came out much better than the B2 Kriek, but still on the watery side, unfortunately. Overall a pleasant sour, with a nice berry note, lots of funk and some sour. Spritzy carbonation, but amping up the fruit and the sweetness from the base to keep it from being on the bland side would be a big improvement. As is, nice stuff, and a big thanks to Joe for sending this my way along with the Kriek.

Batch #2, Bottle #322. This was rather underwhelming. There are some cherries here, but really more gueuze than kriek going on. Theres a bit of a perfumey note that I wasnt a huge fan of, but that went away as it warmed. What this does have going for it is that its much more of a traditional lambic than any other U.S. made sour Ive tried. It was a good beer with plenty of cheesy funk and light cherry. But given its reputation, hard for this not to be a big letdown.
Top notch DIPA, on the more traditional side than the new age citrus and pineapple bombs. A bit of onionyness, nice bitter, sweetnees in the back. Really good stuff.
Interesting brew. Intermingling funk from both the yeast and the galaxy hops here make for a pretty unique flavor. Definitely worth a try, and nicely done.

Top notch, with notes from both the bourbon and rye barrels. Honestly one of the more top notch non-adjunct BA stouts out there. This blew away Rare DOS for me. Really incredible barrel treatment right here.
Smooth, nice roasty porter. Big beer, but drinks easy with low booze level. Chocolate, roast, light hops, good balance between sweet and bitter. Good stuff.

An excellent, super smooth BA stout that I would have any time. Really nice stuff, but theres just so much out there it gets lost in the crowd of excellent beers in the style. Definitely worth grabbing if you have the chance.

Imperial Stout #200! I dont know what to say. One of the best beers Ive ever had. Cinnamon is huge, some coffee spice and roast, chocolate, and huge coconut notes from the barrels. Liquor is very smooth and doesnt come off super hot. Sure it could be thicker, but its rich as hell already. Near perfect.
Super smooth bock with nice sweetness and big malts, but balanced out by light dryness and making it very drinkable. Yum.
On tap at The Top. Nice porter with big coffee notes that really doesnt drink up to the ABV. Pretty decent overall, but nothing overly exciting.
beer_name: Two Brothers Red Eye Coffee Porter

review_blob: Decent hoppy brew. Underwhelming, particularly for using two of my favorite hops. Worth a drink, gets lost in the herd, and doesnt live up to the amazing hoppy beers out there.
beer_name: Cigar City El Centro Citra and Simcoe Dry-Hopped Ale

review_blob: Big roast. Big bitter coffee. Really nice, though not as rich and creamy as I had hoped. Overall good stuff, but I now measure everything up to Sump and this isnt at that level.

Bottle from trade. Easily the best of the "golden" sour beers Ive had. Huge sour punch, almost some peach and tangerine going on here, lighter bodied, but huge flavor. Really nice stuff. Only complaint was that this thing is wicked sour for a large format, and I tried downing it alone. Luckily had plenty of Tums.

Killer saison with lots of brett and lots of funk, nice honey and hay notes. Light sweetness balanced by light bitter hops. Man, this will hold up next to just about anything in the style. Excellent stuff.
I wasnt really into this one. Tasted like champagne, super dry, tough to drink much of this really. Too bad, as I was excited about trying it.
One of the most sour beers Ive had. Solid brew, nice vinous notes, but lots of vinegar and extremely sour. Good stuff, not the best of Avery sours Ive had.
beer_name: Avery Barrel-Aged Series 26 - Tectum et Elix

review_blob: This is truly awful. Pure malt bomb, overly sweet, what in the world? Why even put this out in the current beer market?
Somewhere between a dry and sweet stout, and doesnt really make a nice medium. Not bad, easy drinking, flavors are there, but a bit watery.

2014 bottle from trade. Pours black with small brownish khaki head. Aroma is big vanilla and bourbon galore, a bit of roast. Flavor follows with lots of nutty coffee, vanilla oak, bourbon, and ridiculous amounts of booze notes. Seriously, why make it this high ABV? No reason for that. Aggressive booze thins things out a bit and gets in the way of what seems to be a nicely aged stout. Overall really nice, but just waaaaay too hot.
beer_name: Hangar 24 Barrel Roll No. 03: Pugachevs Cobra - Barrel-Aged Imperial Stout
